dismissalText.commentary: Gary Wilson run out (Masakadza) 65 (55b 6x4 3x6 69m) SR: 118.18

dismissalComment.html: great awareness from Masakadza! Mooney hammered a full one straight back down the pitch, but it clattered into the stumps and stopped dead. Wilson had charged down the pitch, looking for a single, and though he turned back quickly, Masakadza pounced on the ball in a flash and ripped one of the remaining stumps right out of the ground to run him out

he's given him! Joyce must have been expecting more turn, but this one rushed on with the arm as Raza continued round the wicket to the left-hander. Ball missed bat, hit pad, and up went Umpire Matibiri's finger.

Raza has another! He continued round the wicket to the right hander, and this one spun in from what looked like an off stump line to strike the pad. Umpire Matibiri upholds the appeal, and a disappointed Stirling trudges off

well held by Waller at long-off! O'Brien came down the track and chipped the ball, not looking to hit it too hard. He probably hit it a little too well, and Waller rushed in from long-off to hold the simple chance

what a catch! Raza is a bundle of energy down at long on. He'd had a go trying to stop the six that Wilson hit down the ground earlier in the over, and now he's pulled off a stunning catch. O'Brien chipped the ball, possibly looking to go straighter than he did, and Raza sprinted in from long-on. The ball was dying on him all the way, but he leapt forward at the very last moment to pluck it out of the air inches off the ground. That's a great effort, and he celebrates by flinging the ball high in to the clear blue sky

dismissalComment.html: and he's gone! Williams wasn't going to be held back by fielders in the deep, but he's given his wicket away with one aggressive stroke too many. He jumped out at the offspinner again, and wanted to go over long-on. But he didn't get all of it, and <s>Wilson</s> Joyce, who had been at slip, settles under the catch. Easily taken.

gone this time! O'Brien pulled his length back, and also got this delivery to leave the batsman off the pitch. Chamu poked at it, and feathered an edge through to the keeper. O'Brien is ecstatic, he runs into the covers with his arms aeroplaning and is mobbed by his team-mates. That's his 200th wicket for Ireland, across all formats.

commentTextItems.html: he's done it! Ervine backs away, picks up the length quickly and flat-bats the ball straight down the ground. Mid on can't cut it off, and he gets four runs to win the game for his team and register his second ODI ton. Ervine raises his arms, and he's embraced by his captain

commentPostTextItems.html: 5:30pm: We hope you've enjoyed our coverage of today's match. Look out for the match report and a few quotes from Zimbabwe's match-winning batsman. These teams meet in the final ODI on Tuesday, and I'll be back to bring you ball-by-ball coverage of that match. Please join me again! Until then, this is Liam Brickhill saying goodbye.

5:23pm: Zimbabwe seal their first ODI series win for more than two years with a five wicket win at Harare Sports Club. The hosts didn't have the best day in the field, though the pitch was definitely better for batting than the track used in the first ODI had been. Ireland's 268 for 7, which was set up by Paul Stirling's quickfire 72 and Gary Wilson's equally energetic 65, looked a very challenging total, but Zimbabwe built their chase around Ervine's calm knock. He battled through some intense heat, pressure from the bowling, and the odd spell where his timing seemed to be failing to guide Zimbabwe to a morale-boosting series win - reaching a memorable hundred in the process.
And, unsurprisingly, Ervine is Man of the Match for his efforts
Wahid: "Century and win both are coming together. What a day for Craig Ervine!"

commentTextItems.html: very full, and aimed right at middle stump. Ervine can only dig it out back down the pitch

commentPostTextItems.html: Juice Card: "The fans are singing. They deserve it. They'll probably accept this series win as an apology from their team for all the heartbreaks they have taken them through over such a long period. A roller coaster of near misses."

commentTextItems.html: Chigumbura drives, but it's just to the left of mid off and the fielder cuts it off. Ervine calls him through for a single
full, on his legs, and Elton keeps the strike with a glance to fine leg
it's short, and pulled, and for a moment the crowd think that's his ton, but the fielder at fine leg stops it on the bounce
a length delivery is driven into the covers, but without much timing

commentPreTextItems.html: Zimbabwe need seven to win, Ervine needs four for his ton
DanielAlexander: "11th October - This days is for Africa #WakaWaka "

commentTextItems.html: a slower ball from O'Brien, and Chigumbura bends down low to sweep it to fine leg

commentPostTextItems.html: The field comes in for Ervine, a ring of four on the off side.

commentPreTextItems.html: There's a wide second slip in place.

commentTextItems.html: nudged into the leg side, but off the splice and there's no space for a single

commentPreTextItems.html: Srihari: "I know Ervine will certainly take the win over any personal milestone, but I really hope he gets his second ton, for he richly deserves it for anchoring the chase perfectly."

commentTextItems.html: play and a miss outside off! Chigumbura was looking to guide this length delivery down to third man, but the ball zipped past him
four runs for Ervine! Mooney pulled his length back, but Ervine met the ball with a front-foot pull and picked the gap at wide long on to perfection
gosh, this one has slipped out of Mooney's sweaty hand. It loops way down the leg side, a huge wide
on a length, just outside off, and Ervine punches to point
nd Chigumbura slices the ball up and over Wilson's head! The shot, to a wide ball outside off, was top edged and the ball flew well over the fielder, bouncing down to third man

dismissalText.commentary: Sikandar Raza c Joyce b Mooney 33 (29b 1x4 1x6 49m) SR: 113.79

commentTextItems.html: caught in the deep! Raza stepped back and targeted the leg side this time, picking up a length delivery. He hit the ball really well, but also placed it straight into the hands of the man at deep midwicket

Raza isn't holding back! He's a team man, and the team comes first. Mooney floated down a gentle half volley outside off, and Raza crunched an inside out drive over extra cover. One bounce, two bounces and four. Ervine better get a move on if he wants his ton

commentPreTextItems.html: Just 18 needed off four overs for Zimbabwe. There's surely no final twist in this story now. Another change, Mooney on from the Golf Course End.

commentTextItems.html: Ervine steps back to shellack a length delivery out to deep cover, where the ball very nearly bounces up and over the fielder charging in from the rope. But he sticks out a hand to stop it, and they only take a single
full outside off stump, and Raza drives to the cover fielder inside the ring
